body:
Do you have such code in your application:
```C++
  OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_CUDA(session_options, 0);
```
Due to limited resources available, we didn't implement all the opset11 ops on GPU.

Yes I do

> Do you have such code in your application:
> 
> ```c++
>   OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_CUDA(session_options, 0);
> ```

It's odd that it would work with python and not C++. Is this intentional or expected behavior?
> Due to limited resources available, we didn't implement all the opset11 ops on GPU.

> It's odd that it would work with python and not C++. Is this intentional or expected behavior?

No, it shouldn't be the case.

If you configure the log severity level to VERBOSE, you should be able to see in the logs the placement map (which nodes got assigned to which provider). That should give a hint. You can try this in Python like this https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2404#issuecomment-554276559.

On Python the model runs significantly faster and has very low CPU consumption (Mostly GPU). As explained earlier the slowdown is seen on the C++ side. 

I can try the same logging approach in C++ to see which layers get assigned to CPU as compared to the GPU in python.
@CoderHam any findings on this issue regarding the discrepancy?

@faxu Here are the logs: [log_py.txt](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/4252885/log_py.txt) and [log_c.txt](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/4252887/log_c.txt)

On using python only these 4 ops are loaded on CPU. While in C a large number of Gather() and Unsqueeze() are loaded on CPU as well. 
```
2020-02-25 16:34:58.611470538 [I:onnxruntime:Default, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1339 GetCapability] Force fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Gather node name: 
2020-02-25 16:34:58.611589162 [I:onnxruntime:Default, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1339 GetCapability] Force fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Cast node name: 
2020-02-25 16:34:58.611614429 [I:onnxruntime:Default, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1339 GetCapability] Force fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Range node name: 
2020-02-25 16:34:58.611633737 [I:onnxruntime:Default, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1339 GetCapability] Force fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Unsqueeze node name: 
2020-02-25 16:34:58.992312977 [V:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:647 TransformGraph]  Provider: [CPUExecutionProvider]: [Gather (), Cast (), Range (), Unsqueeze (), ]
```

Note: I used the above script mentioned in the issue description to build the Onnx that was used for preparing log_c.txt
However the python version (same i.e. 1.1.1) was installed using pip and not built from source.
@faxu @pranavsharma Could you have a look at the log and verify is this is indeed a bug in the build process?

From the logs, it's clear that the python version runs a bunch of optimizations (fusions) while the C one doesn't. What optimization level did you set when using the C API? Try with ORT_ENABLE_ALL. (It should've been the default starting v1.1.1, but that's a different issue). Please post your C and Python programs here. Also, when you're building you don't need openvino and tensorrt if you just want to use CPU and CUDA execution providers.

Thanks @pranavsharma setting the optimization level to **ENABLE_ALL** worked. I was setting **DISABLE_ALL** earlier and wasn't aware that disabled some GPU ops and forced them to run on CPU. Closing this issue.

Can you help me understand the significance of 
ORT_DISABLE_ALL -> Disables all optimizations (**Does this disable some GPU ops?**)
ORT_ENABLE_BASIC -> Enables basic optimizations (**Which ops on also run on GPU if this is enabled?**) 
ORT_ENABLE_EXTENDED -> Enables basic and extended optimizations 
ORT_ENABLE_ALL -> Enables all available optimizations including layout optimizations

You mentioned ORT_ENABLE_ALL is default. Does this mean that a minimal onnxruntime built without TRT and openvino but _with_ CUDA should support this profile?
